result.execSummary:
The defendant Darrell Dejuan Williams was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Incident, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:50 p.m.  Defendant in custody and present in court with Atty John Selsing.  Andrew Christenson for the State of Wisconsin.  Statement by Atty Selsing - defendant will proceed to sentencing and will plea to Disorderly Conduct - domestic as repeater.  DA confirms compliance with victim witness rights.  Court recites agreement, defendant will enter a plea of NO CONTEST to the amended charge.  State concurs.  Atty Selsing concurs.  Defendant concurs.  

Court goes over plea questionnaire with the defendant.  Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - defendant waives these rights.  Court goes over the elements of each offense as a repeater and as domestic.  Court instructs defendant of the maximum penalty.  Court instructs defendant regarding deportation.    

Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST.  Court finds the plea is made freely, voluntarily, intelligently and understandingly.  Court finds there is a factual basis to support the plea.  Court finds the defendant guilty to the amended charge.  Court orders the judgment of conviction be entered here today.  Sentencing statement by DA.  Sentencing statement by Atty Selsing.  No statement by the defendant.

Court sentences the defendant to:

4 months county jail consecutive to any other sentnece the defendant may be serving.  Sentence is to commence immediately.

Court costs - 60 days to pay or payment plan.
